  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Promoting resilience through increased access to quality -formal education and psycho-social support for conflict-affected children in Northern Syria under Envelop 1 of Standard Allocation.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed project is designed to address the strategic priorities raised in the new allocation paper and respond to the objectives of the Education cluster by providing Educational support and integrated protection and referral services to a total of 11 conflict affected communities with high needs leading to dignified and safer living conditions.

This project aims to support the lives of targeted communities in Northern Syria through the provision of formal education, psychosocial support (PSS) and referral services contributing to improving education and individual development of children and youth in Syria and allowing them to foster resilience and give them a chance at a better future.

The project will focus on the provision of access to inclusive, safe and quality learning environments for a total of 9800 conflict-affected children (4370 boys | 4530 girls). Through the distribution of all essential items and materials for high quality and safe learning (operational items, stationary and other learning and teaching materials, textbooks, etc.), as well as ensuring safe access to integrated PSS activities for all students.

The proposed action will have the duration of 12 months commencing from July 2022 prior to the start of the educational school year and will be implemented in Armanaz, Binnesh, Harim, Atareb, Maret Tamsarin, Ariha and Idlib sub districts which have the highest need as per the allocation&#x2019;s prioritized list of locations. PIN is committed to all humanitarian principles, Code of Conduct, Child protection, PSEA and other essential policies, having a robust Accountability system at place as well, ensuring a high quality project implementation in line with all the requirements of SCHF.</narrative>
  </description>
